{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"7e6d723f5ecd8dee","x":-2760,"y":-1160,"width":1880,"height":1860,"type":"group"},
		{"id":"l5_bg","type":"group","x":-2080,"y":-1065,"width":520,"height":1745,"color":"2","label":"L5 · Autonomous Management — OpenClaw Agent"},
		{"id":"l4_bg","type":"group","x":-1360,"y":-220,"width":460,"height":900,"color":"5","label":"L4 · Collaborative Agent Systems"},
		{"id":"l1_bg","type":"group","x":-2740,"y":-1020,"width":420,"height":800,"color":"4","label":"L1 · Basic Log Parser & Responder"},
		{"id":"l3_bg","type":"group","x":-2740,"y":-120,"width":440,"height":760,"color":"3","label":"L3 · Multi-Source Integration  ✦ Production Sweet Spot"},
		{"id":"l2_bg","type":"group","x":-1360,"y":-1010,"width":420,"height":670,"color":"1","label":"L2 · Pattern Recognition & Routing"},
		{"id":"l1_what","type":"text","text":"### What it does\n\n- Read any log format\n- Summarise error patterns\n- Answer plain-language questions like \"why did the app crash?\"\n- Stateless — no memory between runs","x":-2720,"y":-980,"width":380,"height":230,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"l4_arch","type":"text","text":"### Architecture\n\nOrchestrator spawns specialist subagents in parallel. Findings merge back through the orchestrator into a unified incident report.\n\n- `infra_agent` — infrastructure & system logs\n- `security_agent` — auth & anomaly detection\n- `app_agent` — application-level errors","x":-1340,"y":-200,"width":420,"height":240,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"l4_skills","type":"text","text":"### Claude Code — Skills & Subagents Pattern\n\n**SKILL.md** — Each specialist agent is a reusable markdown skill file defining its persona, tools, and output format. The orchestrator reads the skill before spawning the subagent.\n\n**Task blocks** — Subagents run via `Task` blocks in isolated contexts with scoped tool permissions. Each subagent cannot see sibling agent state.\n\n**Routing** — Security anomaly → `security_agent/SKILL.md`. DB timeout → `infra_agent/SKILL.md`. Skills are hot-swappable without touching orchestrator logic.\n\n**Memory** — Shared JSON scratchpad, orchestrator-controlled. Subagents read from it; only the orchestrator writes final conclusions. Prevents conflicting memory writes across parallel agents.","x":-1340,"y":50,"width":420,"height":410,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"l2_what","type":"text","text":"### What it does\n\n- P1 / P2 / P3 severity triage\n- Route alerts to the correct team\n- Trigger known-pattern scripts\n- Deduplicate repeat alerts via state file\n\n**Pattern:** ReAct (Reason → Act)","x":-1340,"y":-970,"width":380,"height":220,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"l2_arch","type":"text","text":"### Architecture\n\nLogs → LLM → `{severity, team, action}` JSON → integration layer → Slack / PagerDuty → JSON state file for deduplication","x":-1340,"y":-730,"width":380,"height":140,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"l2_risk","type":"text","text":"### ⚠️ Risk Note\n\nAutomated actions can mis-page or mis-restart. **Start read-only** (create tickets, send info alerts). Expand to restarts only after validating agent judgment in staging.","x":-1340,"y":-570,"width":380,"height":200,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"l3_sources","type":"text","text":"### Live Sources\n\n- **Elasticsearch** — application logs\n- **Kubernetes** — container logs\n- **CloudWatch** — system metrics\n- **RDS** — database logs","x":-2720,"y":-80,"width":400,"height":180,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"l3_killer","type":"text","text":"### Killer Feature — Cross-System Correlation\n\nInstead of \"service crashed\" → it says:\n\n> \"Service crashed after DB connection pool exhausted, caused by a deploy that changed timeout from 30s → 5s.\"\n\nFull root-cause chain, not just symptoms.","x":-2720,"y":120,"width":400,"height":240,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"l3_arch","type":"text","text":"### Architecture\n\nMultiple API clients → aggregation pipeline → normalise log formats → unified context → LLM → structured incident report\n\n~1,000–3,000 lines. Proper modules, rate-limit handling, caching, error handling for API outages.","x":-2720,"y":380,"width":400,"height":220,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"l5_openclaw","type":"text","text":"### OpenClaw Agent Model\n\nAn OpenClaw-style autonomous agent that detects, plans, and remediates incidents end-to-end. Self-improves by learning which fixes worked.\n\n**But unlike fully autonomous Level 5:** every high-impact action pauses at a human approval gate before execution — combining agent speed with human judgment.\n\n🟢 **Human-in-the-loop required for all critical actions**","x":-2060,"y":-1025,"width":460,"height":280,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"l5_arch","type":"text","text":"### Architecture\n\nMonitoring stream → OpenClaw planner → remediation plan → **Human Approval UI** (approve / reject / modify) → sandboxed tool execution → outcome logged → model updated\n\nAll agent identity uses scoped, short-lived credentials. Every action is immutably logged. Kill switch always available.","x":-2060,"y":-725,"width":460,"height":255,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"l5_owasp","type":"text","text":"## 🔐 OWASP Agentic Security — OpenClaw Implementation\n*Source: genai.owasp.org*\n\n**ASI01 — System Prompt Lock**\nSystem prompt locked at init, all log inputs sanitised before planner sees them.\n\n**ASI02 — Tool Scoping**\nEvery tool call scoped; shell/DB/cloud actions blocked until human approves.\n\n**ASI03 — IAM Role Isolation**\nOpenClaw runs under its own short-lived IAM role, never a user session.\n\n**ASI04 — Message Signing**\nOrchestrator signs messages to subagents; unsigned instructions rejected.\n\n**ASI05 — Scratchpad Hygiene**\nPlanner writes summaries to scratchpad, never raw log content.\n\n**ASI06 — Plugin Pinning**\nMCP servers and tool plugins pinned to verified hashes at startup.\n\n**ASI07 — Authenticated Bus**\nAll inter-agent messages go through authenticated internal message bus.\n\n**ASI08 — Digital Twin Staging**\nActions tested in digital-twin env first, blast-radius cap enforced.\n\n**ASI09 — Separate Approval Surface**\nApproval UI is a separate surface, never inside the agent chat.\n\n**ASI10 — Kill Switch**\nKill switch on every agent process, behavioural anomaly monitor always on.","x":-2060,"y":-432,"width":460,"height":1072,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"l1_why","type":"text","text":"### Why start here\n\nMaster prompt structure first. Have a working tool in an afternoon. Discover what you actually need before building more.\n\n**Pill:** Foundation","x":-2720,"y":-432,"width":380,"height":198,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"l1_arch","type":"text","text":"### Architecture\n\n`open(log)` → prompt builder → LLM → output\n\n~100–150 lines of Python. No database, no integrations. A well-crafted system prompt is all that matters here.","x":-2720,"y":-702,"width":380,"height":210,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"l4_cost","type":"text","text":"### Complexity Cost\n\nMultiple model instances = higher cost. Debugging is harder — which agent made which decision? Most teams should stick at L3 unless they have specific scaling or domain-specialisation requirements.","x":-1340,"y":490,"width":420,"height":180,"color":"3"}
	],
